2. IOC (Inversion of Control)
Definition: Instead of your code creating and managing objects, you hand that responsibility to the Spring IOC Container. The container creates objects, configures them, and manages their entire lifecycle.
Without Spring	With Spring (IOC)
Engine e = new Engine();  Car c = new Car(e);	You just declare the need. Spring creates Engine, creates Car, and injects Engine into Car.

Why it matters: Loose coupling. Your Car class doesn't know or care how Engine was created — easier to test, swap implementations, and maintain.
The container itself has two main flavors:
•	BeanFactory – basic container, lazy loading (older, rarely used directly)
•	ApplicationContext – advanced container, eager loading, most commonly used in real projects (this is what you'll use 99% of the time)
ApplicationContext context = new ClassPathXmlApplicationContext("beans.xml");
Car car = (Car) context.getBean("car");

Key phrase for exams: "IOC is the principle; DI is the implementation technique Spring uses to achieve IOC."

3. Dependency Injection (DI) and Its Types
DI = the process of the container "injecting" the dependent object into a class, rather than the class creating it itself.
Type 1: Constructor Injection
Dependency is passed via the constructor. Best for mandatory dependencies.
public class Car {
    private Engine engine;
 
    public Car(Engine engine) {   // injected via constructor
        this.engine = engine;
    }
}

XML:
<bean id="car" class="com.example.Car">
    <constructor-arg ref="engine"/>
</bean>

Type 2: Setter Injection
Dependency is set via a setter method. Best for optional dependencies.
public class Car {
    private Engine engine;
 
    public void setEngine(Engine engine) {   // injected via setter
        this.engine = engine;
    }
}

XML:
<bean id="car" class="com.example.Car">
    <property name="engine" ref="engine"/>
</bean>

Type 3: Field Injection
Dependency injected directly into the field using @Autowired (annotation-based, no XML needed). Common in real projects but not recommended for testing purposes.
public class Car {
    @Autowired
    private Engine engine;
}

Exam-style comparison table:
Aspect	Constructor Injection	Setter Injection
Dependency type	Mandatory	Optional
Immutability	Object is immutable once created	Can be changed after creation
Circular dependency	Fails	Can work
Preferred by Spring team	Yes	Situational

4. Bean Scopes and Lifecycle
Bean Scopes (how many instances Spring creates)
Scope	Meaning
singleton (default)	Only one instance per Spring container, shared everywhere
prototype	New instance every time the bean is requested
request	New instance per HTTP request (web apps only)
session	New instance per HTTP session (web apps only)

<bean id="car" class="com.example.Car" scope="prototype"/>
or with annotation:
@Scope("prototype")
@Component
public class Car { }

Exam trap: singleton scope is not the Singleton design pattern. Singleton scope means one instance per container, not one instance per JVM.
Bean Lifecycle (order — commonly asked!)
•	Container starts -> Bean instantiated (constructor called)
•	Dependencies injected (setter/constructor injection happens)
•	setBeanName(), setBeanFactory() (Aware interfaces, if implemented)
•	@PostConstruct method / init-method called -> custom initialization logic
•	Bean is ready and in use
•	Container shuts down -> @PreDestroy method / destroy-method called -> cleanup logic
public class Car {
    @PostConstruct
    public void init() {
        System.out.println("Car bean initialized");
    }
 
    @PreDestroy
    public void cleanup() {
        System.out.println("Car bean about to be destroyed");
    }
}

XML equivalent:
<bean id="car" class="com.example.Car" init-method="init" destroy-method="cleanup"/>

Memory hook: Instantiate -> Inject -> Initialize -> Use -> Destroy (I-I-I-U-D)

5. XML Configuration
Old-school but still asked in exams/interviews. Config lives in a separate beans.xml file.
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<beans xmlns="http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans"
       xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
       xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans
       http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans/spring-beans.xsd">
 
    <bean id="engine" class="com.example.Engine"/>
 
    <bean id="car" class="com.example.Car">
        <constructor-arg ref="engine"/>
    </bean>
 
</beans>

Loading it in Java:
ApplicationContext context = new ClassPathXmlApplicationContext("beans.xml");
Car car = context.getBean(Car.class);

Key tags:
•	<bean id="..." class="..."> – declares a bean
•	<property name="..." ref="..."/> – setter injection
•	<constructor-arg ref="..."/> – constructor injection
•	<property name="..." value="..."/> – inject primitive/String values directly

6. Autowiring and Its Types
Autowiring = Spring automatically resolves and injects dependencies, without you writing <constructor-arg> or <property> tags manually.
Type	How it matches	XML syntax
byName	Matches bean id with the property/setter name	autowire="byName"
byType	Matches by data type (fails if 2+ beans of same type exist)	autowire="byType"
constructor	Like byType, but for constructor arguments	autowire="constructor"
no (default)	No autowiring, manual wiring only	autowire="no"

<bean id="car" class="com.example.Car" autowire="byType"/>

Annotation-based autowiring (most used today):
@Component
public class Car {
    @Autowired   // Spring auto-injects a matching Engine bean by type
    private Engine engine;
}

Exam trap: If byType finds more than one matching bean, it throws NoUniqueBeanDefinitionException. Fix it with @Qualifier("beanName") to specify exactly which bean to inject.
@Autowired
@Qualifier("petrolEngine")
private Engine engine;

7. Java Configuration and Annotations
Modern Spring avoids XML almost entirely, using annotations + Java config classes instead.
Key annotations
Annotation	Purpose
@Configuration	Marks a class as a source of bean definitions (replaces XML file)
@Bean	Marks a method whose return value becomes a Spring bean
@Component	Marks a class to be auto-detected and registered as a bean
@Autowired	Auto-injects a dependency
@Qualifier	Resolves ambiguity when multiple beans of the same type exist
@ComponentScan	Tells Spring which package(s) to scan for @Component classes
@Service, @Repository, @Controller	Specializations of @Component for specific layers

Java Config example (equivalent to the XML above)
@Configuration
@ComponentScan(basePackages = "com.example")
public class AppConfig {
 
    @Bean
    public Engine engine() {
        return new Engine();
    }
 
    @Bean
    public Car car() {
        return new Car(engine());   // constructor injection via Java config
    }
}

Loading it:
ApplicationContext context = new AnnotationConfigApplicationContext(AppConfig.class);
Car car = context.getBean(Car.class);

Exam comparison — XML vs Java Config vs Annotation-only:
Approach	Where beans are declared	Verbosity
XML	beans.xml	High
Java Config	@Configuration class with @Bean methods	Medium
Annotation (@Component + scan)	On the class itself	Low

8. Reading Values from a Properties File
Instead of hardcoding values like DB URLs or passwords, store them in a .properties file and inject them.
application.properties:
app.name=MySpringApp
app.version=1.0
db.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydb

Method 1: XML approach
<context:property-placeholder location="classpath:application.properties"/>
 
<bean id="car" class="com.example.Car">
    <property name="name" value="${app.name}"/>
</bean>

Method 2: Java Config approach
@Configuration
@PropertySource("classpath:application.properties")
public class AppConfig {
 
    @Value("${app.name}")
    private String appName;
}

Method 3: Direct field injection with @Value
@Component
public class Car {
    @Value("${app.version}")
    private String version;
}

Exam trap: @PropertySource only loads the file — you still need @Value("${key}") to actually pull individual values into fields. And PropertySourcesPlaceholderConfigurer (or <context:property-placeholder> in XML) must be registered for ${...} placeholders to resolve.

Quick Revision Cheat Sheet (day-before-exam skim)
•	Maven = build + dependency tool; pom.xml is the config; lifecycle = validate -> compile -> test -> package -> install
•	IOC = container controls object creation, not your code
•	DI = the technique (constructor / setter / field) used to achieve IOC
•	Singleton scope = one bean per container (default); Prototype = new bean every request
•	Bean lifecycle = Instantiate -> Inject -> @PostConstruct -> Use -> @PreDestroy
•	Autowiring types = byName, byType, constructor, no
•	@Qualifier fixes ambiguity when byType finds multiple matches
•	Java Config = @Configuration + @Bean replaces XML <bean> tags
•	@Component/@Service/@Repository = auto-detected beans via @ComponentScan
•	@Value("${key}") + @PropertySource = reading from properties files

